<DOC><DOCNO> AP880614-0160 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0049EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   06-14 0512</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0534</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Legislation to close a loophole in theregulation of polychlorinated biphenyls, the highly toxic chemicalswhose manufacture was banned in 1976, has been approved by theHouse.   The bill, sent to the Senate Monday, would require brokers, themiddlemen who arrange for the transportation and destruction ofPCBs, to be registered, keep records and demonstrate financialresponsibility.   Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, said the legislation is a response toreports that unregulated PCB brokers have handled the chemicalsimproperly and in some instances have gone bankrupt, leaving powercompanies and communities to clean up PCB storage sites.</TEXT><DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American Brands Inc. says it is sellingits recently-acquired subsidiary E-II Holdings to an affiliate ofthe privately- held Riklis Family Corp. for $950 million in cashand $250 million in securities.   American Brands said Monday it will buy back seven companiesincluding five that it expects will accelerate development of itsemerging core businesses in hardware and home products and officeproducts.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An investor group planning to acquire BraniffInc. for about $100 million said it intends to expand the airlineand will guarantee job security to Braniff employees for at leastthree years.   Monday's announcement came three days after Braniff's majorityowner, the Pritzker family of Chicago, said it would sell its 64percent stake to an investor group formed by Paine Webber Group Inc.   Braniff lost an estimated $100 million in the Prizkers' firstyear of ownership in 1983. It lost $9.02 million in 1987.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan has called for a joint effortto restore the economies of Afghanistan and the Philippines and aninternational crackdown on money laundering from illegal drugs.   Reagan also said Monday he would prod world leaders to completenegotiations by the end of the year to cut back on agriculturalsubsidies, which cost an estimated $200 billion a year in Europe,North America and Japan.   On Sunday, Reagan will fly to Toronto for his eighth and finalsummit with the leaders of Britain, France, West Germany, Canada,Japan and Italy.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Interest rates on short-term Treasurysecurities were mixed in the government's latest auction, withthree-month securities unchanged and the six-month rate downslightly.   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month billsat an average discount rate of 6.44 percent Monday, identical tolast week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at anaverage discount rate of 6.67 percent, down from 6.72 percent lastweek.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market held its ground ahead of a key report on thenation's trade deficit in April. The Dow Jones average of 30 bluechips fell 2.31 points to close at 2,099.40.   Bond prices edged higher as oil prices slipped and traderslooked ahead to trade figures.   The dollar rose slightly against other major currencies.   Soybean futures prices sagged but grain futures finished mixed,reflecting uncertainty about the amount of moisture thatdrought-ridden croplands are likely to receive.</TEXT></DOC>